        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Python does not update the dict before it assigns variables, as you can see here:\r\n```python\r\nPython 3.8.10 (default, Jun 22 2022, 20:18:18) \r\n[GCC 9.4.0] on linux\r\nType \"help\", \"copyright\", \"credits\" or \"license\" for more information.\r\n>>> def cython_locals_test():\r\n...     a = locals()\r\n...     b = locals()\r\n...     return a, b, a == b, a is b\r\n... \r\n>>> cython_locals_test()\r\n({'a': {...}}, {'a': {...}}, True, True)\r\n>>> def test2():\r\n...     a = dict(locals())\r\n...     b = dict(locals())\r\n...     return a, b, a == b, a is b\r\n... \r\n>>> test2()\r\n({}, {'a': {}}, False, False)\r\n```\r\nHowever, it does always return the same dict for `locals()` and updates it when you call `locals()`. That does not mean that an assignment leads to new entries in that dict. In fact, really only calling `locals()` changes the content, as you can see here:\r\n```python\r\n>>> def test3():\r\n...     a = locals()\r\n...     b = locals()\r\n...     c = dict(b)\r\n...     locals()\r\n...     return a, b, c\r\n... \r\n>>> test3()\r\n({'a': {...}, 'b': {...}, 'c': {'a': {...}}}, {'a': {...}, 'b': {...}, 'c': {'a': {...}}}, {'a': {'a': {...}, 'b': {...}, 'c': {...}}})\r\n```\r\n\r\nCython currently behaves slightly differently in that it creates a new dict on each access. That's ok for most use cases, but obviously differs from Python's behaviour if you explicitly look for the difference, as you do in your example.\r\n\r\nI don't see a real difference in practice, though. If you want an up-to-date version of locals(), ask for it.",
